<subsection xml:id="subsec-enlargement">
    <title>Enlargement</title>
    <p>
        Enlargement is a transformation that increases the size of a shape. The shape is enlarged by a scale factor. The scale factor is used to multiply the length of each side of the shape to get the length of the corresponding side of the enlarged shape.
    </p>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                 <m>{\color{blue} \text{Work in groups.}}</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                In the figure 3.1, <m>ABC</m> is a triangle in which <m>AB=2.2</m> <m>cm</m>, <m>BC=1.8</m> <m>cm</m> and <m>AC=4.5</m> <m>cm</m>.<m>O</m> is a point such that <m>OA=4.5</m> <m>cm</m>, <m>OB=3</m> <m>cm</m> and <m>OC=4</m> <m>cm</m>.
            </p>

            <image width="50%">
                <shortdescription>Fig 3.1</shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="Triangle2">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        
                        % Define coordinates
                        \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (C) at (3,0);
                        \coordinate (B) at (2.2,1.1);  
                        \coordinate (A) at (2.5,3);
                        
                        \coordinate (C') at (6,0);
                        \coordinate (B') at (4.4,2.2);  
                        \coordinate (A') at (5,6);
                        
                        % Draw base triangles
                        \draw (O) -- (C);
                        \draw (O) -- (C');
                        \draw (C) -- (B) -- (A) -- cycle;
                        \draw (C') -- (B') -- (A') -- cycle;
                        
                        % Draw ONE straight line passing through O, Q, and Q'
                        \draw (O) -- (B) -- (B');

                        % Draw straight line from O to P and P'
                        \draw (O) -- (A) -- (A');

                        % Shade the inner triangles with different colors
                        \fill[blue!50,opacity=0.6] (C) -- (B) -- (A) -- cycle;  % Blue triangle
                        \fill[cyan!50,opacity=0.6] (C') -- (B') -- (A') -- cycle; % Cyan triangle
                        
                        % Label points
                        \node[above left] at (O) {O};
                        \node[below] at (C) {C};
                        \node[below] at (C') {C'};
                        \node[above] at (A) {A};
                        \node[above] at (A') {A'};
                        \node[left] at (B) {B};
                        \node[right] at (B') {B'};

                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                
            </image>

            <p>
                Triangle <m>A'B'C'</m> has been obtained from triangle <m>ABC</m> as follows:
            </p>

            <p>
                <m>OA</m>, <m>OB</m> and <m>OC</m> are produced such that <m>OA'=13.5</m> <m>cm</m>, <m>OB'=9</m> <m>cm</m> and <m>OC'=12</m> <m>cm</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                The process of obtaining triangle <m>A'B'C'</m> from triangle <m>ABC</m> is known as <m>{\color{blue} \text{enlargement.}}</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                Triangle <m>ABC</m> is said to be object and triangle <m>A'B'C'</m>, its image under enlargement.The point <m>O</m> is known as the <m>{\color{blue} \text{centre of enlargement.}}</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                <m>{\color{blue} \text{Point to note.}}</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                \frac{OA'}{OA} = \frac{OB'}{OB} = \frac{OC'}{OC} =3
                            </me>
                            
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                 \frac{A'B'}{AB} = \frac{A'C'}{AC} = \frac{B'C'}{BC} =3
                            </me>
                            
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <p>
                The scale factor of this enlargement is <m>3</m>.In an enlargement, the object and its image remain similar. The linear scale factor of the enlargement determines the proportional transformation.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <p>
        To determine the scale factor, divide the length of the enlarged image by the corresponding length of the original object.
    </p>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                In the figure below, Triangle <m>P'Q'R'</m> is  the enlarged image of triangle <m>PQR</m>, with center <m>O</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                (a). Given that <m>OP=6</m> <m>cm</m> and <m>PP'=9</m> <m>cm</m>, determine the scale factor of the enlargement.
            </p>

            <p>
                (b). If <m>QR=4</m> <m>cm</m>, find the length of <m>Q'R'</m>
            </p>

            <image width="50%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="Triangle1">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (R) at (3,0);
                    \coordinate (Q) at (2.2,1.1);  
                    \coordinate (P) at (2.5,3);

                    \coordinate (R') at (6,0);
                    \coordinate (Q') at (4.4,2.2);  
                    \coordinate (P') at (5,6);

                    % Draw base triangles
                    \draw (O) -- (R);
                    \draw (O) -- (R');
                    \draw (R) -- (Q) -- (P) -- cycle;
                    \draw (R') -- (Q') -- (P') -- cycle;

                    % Draw ONE straight line passing through O, Q, and Q'
                    \draw (O) -- (Q) -- (Q');

                    % Draw straight line from O to P and P'
                    \draw (O) -- (P) -- (P');

                    % Shade the inner triangles with different colors
                    \fill[blue!50,opacity=0.6] (R) -- (Q) -- (P) -- cycle;  % Blue triangle
                    \fill[cyan!50,opacity=0.6] (R') -- (Q') -- (P') -- cycle; % Cyan triangle

                    % Label points
                    \node[above left] at (O) {O};
                    \node[below] at (R) {R};
                    \node[below] at (R') {R'};
                    \node[above] at (P) {P};
                    \node[above] at (P') {P'};
                    \node[left] at (Q) {Q};
                    \node[right] at (Q') {Q'};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                
            </image>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text {(a). Linear scale factor is:} \amp </mrow>
                    <mrow> \frac {OP'}{OP} =\amp \frac{(6+9)}{6}</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{15}{6}</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac {5}{2}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text {(b).Lenear scale factor } =\amp \frac {Q'R'}{QR}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text {But QR}  =\amp 4\, cm </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text {Therefore,} \frac {Q'R'}{QR}= \amp \frac {5}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>Q'P' =\amp \frac{(4 \times 5)}{2} </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{20}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow> Q'P' = \amp 10\, cm</mrow>

                </md>
            </p>
            
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Construct any triangle <m>XYZ</m> and choose a point <m>O</m> outside the triangle. Using <m>O</m> as the center of enlargement and a scale factor of <m>4</m>, construct the enlarged image of triangle <m>XYZ</m> under the enlargement.
            </p>

        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                
            </p>

            <image width="50%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="Triangle3">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Define coordinates
                        \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (Z) at (3,0);
                        \coordinate (Y) at (2.2,1.1);  
                        \coordinate (X) at (2.5,3);

                        \coordinate (Z') at (6,0);
                        \coordinate (Y') at (4.4,2.2);  
                        \coordinate (X') at (5,6);

                        % Draw base triangles
                        \draw (O) -- (Z);
                        \draw (O) -- (Z');
                        \draw (Z) -- (Y) -- (X) -- cycle;
                        \draw (Z') -- (Y') -- (X') -- cycle;

                        % Draw ONE straight line passing through O, Y, and Y'
                        \draw (O) -- (Y) -- (Y');

                        % Draw straight line from O to X and X'
                        \draw (O) -- (X) -- (X');

                        % Shade the inner triangles with different colors
                        \fill[yellow!60,opacity=0.6] (Z) -- (Y) -- (X) -- cycle;  % Yellow triangle
                        \fill[orange!60,opacity=0.6] (Z') -- (Y') -- (X') -- cycle; % Orange triangle

                        % Draw right angle signs inside triangles at Y and Y'
                        \draw (Y) ++(0.2,0) -- ++(0,0.2) -- ++(-0.2,0);
                        \draw (Y') ++(0.2,0) -- ++(0,0.2) -- ++(-0.2,0);

                        % Label points
                        \node[above left] at (O) {O};
                        \node[below] at (Z) {Z};
                        \node[below] at (Z') {Z'};
                        \node[above] at (X) {X};
                        \node[above] at (X') {X'};
                        \node[left] at (Y) {Y};
                        \node[right] at (Y') {Y'};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                
            </image>

            <p>
                By measurement;
            </p>

            <p>
                <m>OX=1.8</m> <m>cm</m>, <m>OY=3.2</m> <m>cm</m> and <m>OZ=2.7</m> <m>cm</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{To determine X', the image of X, We follow these steps:} \amp </mrow>
                    <mrow>OX= \amp 1.8\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac {OX'}{OX}= \amp \text{scale factor}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{OX'}{1.8} =4\amp </mrow>
                    <mrow>OX'= \amp 4 \times 1.8\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 7.2\, cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Extend <m>OX</m> and measure <m>7.2</m> <m>cm</m> from <m>O</m> to get <m>X'</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{To determine Y', the image of Y, We follow these steps:} \amp </mrow>
                     <mrow>OY= \amp 3.2\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac {OY'}{OY}= \amp \text{scale factor}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{OY'}{3.2} =4\amp </mrow>
                    <mrow>OX'= \amp 4 \times 3.2\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 12.8\, cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Extend <m>OY</m> and measure <m>12.8</m> <m>cm</m> from <m>O</m> to get <m>Y'</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{To determine Z', the image of Z, We follow these steps:} \amp </mrow>
                     <mrow>OZ= \amp 2.7\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac {OZ'}{OZ}= \amp \text{scale factor}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{OZ'}{2.7} =4\amp </mrow>
                    <mrow>OX'= \amp 4 \times 2.7\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 10.8\, cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Extend <m>OZ</m> and measure <m>10.8</m> <m>cm</m> from <m>O</m> to get <m>Z'</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

